[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] In optimization, **2-opt** is a simple local search algorithm for solving the traveling salesman problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] The 2-opt algorithm was first proposed by Croes in 1958, although the basic move had already been suggested by Flood.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] The main idea behind it is to take a route that crosses over itself and reorder it so that it does not.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] A complete 2-opt local search will compare every possible valid combination of the swapping mechanism.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] This technique can be applied to the traveling salesman problem as well as many related problems.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] These include the vehicle routing problem (VRP) as well as the capacitated VRP, which require minor modification of the algorithm.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] In pseudocode, the mechanism by which the 2-opt swap manipulates a given route is as follows.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] The particular nodes or depots that are at the start and at the end of the path should be removed from the search as an eligible candidates for swapping, as reversing the order would cause an invalid path.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] which is not valid (does not leave from A, the depot).
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] Building the new route and calculating the distance of the new route can be a very expensive operation, usually $O(n)$ where n is the number of vertices in the route.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] In a symmetric case (where the distance between A and B is the same as between B and A), this can be skipped by performing a $O(1)$ operation.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] Since a 2-opt operation involves removing 2 edges and adding 2 different edges we can subtract and add the distances of only those edges.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] If `lengthDelta` is negative that would mean that the new distance after the swap would be smaller.
[src:lin-kernighan/2-opt] Once it is known that `lengthDelta` is negative, then we perform a 2-opt swap.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] In optimization, **3-opt** is a simple local search heuristic for finding approximate solutions to the travelling salesperson problem and related network optimization problems.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] Compared to the simpler 2-opt algorithm, it is slower but can generate higher-quality solutions.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] 3-opt analysis involves deleting three edges from the current solution to the problem, creating three sub-tours.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] There are eight ways of connecting these sub-tours back into a single tour, one of which consists of the three deleted edges.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] These reconnections are analysed to find the optimum one.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] This process is then repeated for a different set of 3 connections, until all possible combinations have been tried in a network.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] A single pass through all triples of edges has a time complexity of $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] Iterated 3-opt, in which passes are repeated until no more improvements can be found, has a higher time complexity.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] Note that the segments $S_{1}$ and $S_{4}$ are connected.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] The reconnection of the Subtours is done by a combination of reversing one or both of $S_{2}$ and $S_{3}$ and switching their respective positions.
[src:lin-kernighan/3-opt] Here ${\overleftrightarrow {S_{i}}}$ indicates that segment i is reversed.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] In combinatorial optimization, **Lin–Kernighan** is one of the best heuristics for solving the symmetric travelling salesman problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Lin–Kernighan is adaptive and has no fixed number of edges to replace at a step, but favours small numbers such as 2 or 3.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] For a given instance $(G,c)$ of the travelling salesman problem, tours are uniquely determined by their sets of edges, so we may as well encode them as such.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] since $g(T\mathbin {\triangle } T')=\sum _{e\in T}c(e)-\sum _{e\in T'}c(e)$ : how much longer the current tour T is than the new tour $T'$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Naively k -opt can be regarded as examining all $F\subseteq \mathrm {E} (G)$ with exactly $2k$ elements ( k in T but not in $T'$ , and another k in $T'$ but not in T ) such that $T\mathbin {\triangle } F$ is again a tour, looking for such a set which has $g(F)>0$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] It is however easier to do those tests in the opposite order: first search for plausible F with positive gain, and only second check if $T\mathbin {\triangle } F$ is in fact a tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Define a trail in G to be **alternating** (with respect to T ) if its edges are alternatingly in T and not in T , respectively.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Hence (essentially by Hierholzer's algorithm for finding Eulerian circuits) the graph $G[T\mathbin {\triangle } T']$ decomposes into closed alternating trails.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Alternating trails (closed or open) are built by extending a shorter alternating trail, so when exploring the neighbourhood of the current tour T , one is exploring a search tree of alternating trails.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The key idea of the Lin–Kernighan algorithm is to remove from this tree all alternating trails which have gain $\leq 0$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] This does not prevent finding every closed trail with positive gain, thanks to the following lemma.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Here the lemma implies that there for every closed alternating trail with positive gain exists at least one starting vertex $v_{0}$ for which all the gains of the partial trails are positive as well, so F will be found when the search explores the branch of alternating trails starting at $v_{0}$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] This yields the following algorithm for finding all closed, positive gain alternating trails in the graph.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] As an enumeration algorithm this is slightly flawed, because it may report the same trail multiple times, with different starting points, but Lin–Kernighan does not care because it mostly aborts the enumeration after finding the first hit.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The basic form of the Lin–Kernighan algorithm not only does a local search counterpart of the above enumeration, but it also introduces two parameters that narrow the search.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Lin & Kernighan report $2.2$ as an empirical exponent of n in the average overall running time for their algorithm, but other implementors have had trouble reproducing that result.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] It appears unlikely that the worst-case running time is polynomial.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] be the top element on the stack (peek, not pop).
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] (update current tour) and clear the stack.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The length of the alternating trails considered are thus not explicitly bounded, but beyond the backtracking depth $p_{1}$ no more than one way of extending the current trail is considered, which in principle stops those explorations from raising the exponent in the runtime complexity.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The closed alternating trails found by the above method are all connected, but the symmetric difference $T\mathbin {\triangle } T'$ of two tours need not be, so in general this method of alternating trails cannot explore the full neighbourhood of a trail T .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The literature on the Lin–Kernighan heuristic uses the term *sequential* exchanges for those that are described by a single alternating trail.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The smallest non-sequential exchange would however replace 4 edges and consist of two cycles of 4 edges each (2 edges added, 2 removed), so it is long compared to the typical Lin–Kernighan exchange, and there are few of these compared to the full set of 4-edge exchanges.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The literature is vague on exactly what is included in the Lin–Kernighan heuristic proper, and what constitutes further refinements.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] For the *asymmetric* TSP, the idea of using positive gain alternating trails to find favourable exchanges is less useful, because there are fewer ways in which pieces of a tour can be rearranged to yield new tours when one may not reverse the orientation of a piece.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Two pieces can only be patched together to reproduce the original tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Three pieces can be patched together to form a different tour in one way only, and the corresponding alternating trail does not extend to a closed trail for rearranging four pieces into a new tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] To rearrange four pieces, one needs a non-sequential exchange.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The Lin–Kernighan heuristic checks the validity of tour candidates $T\mathbin {\triangle } F$ at two points: obviously when deciding whether a better tour has been found, but also as a constraint to descending in the search tree, as controlled via the infeasibility depth $p_{2}$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] By design that set of edges constitutes a 2-factor in G , so what needs to be determined is whether that 2-factor consists of a single Hamiltonian cycle, or instead is made up of several cycles.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] If naively posing this subproblem as giving a subroutine the set of n edges as input, one ends up with $O(n)$ as the time complexity for this check, since it is necessary to walk around the full tour before being able to determine that it is in fact a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] That is too slow for the second usage of this test, which gets carried out for every alternating trail with more than 2 edges from T .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] If keeping track of more information, the test can instead be carried out in constant time.
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] A useful degree of freedom here is that one may choose the order in which step 2.3.2 iterates over all vertices; in particular, one may follow the known tour T .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] The outcome of the Hamiltonicity test done when considering the $(k+1)$ th edge $v_{2k}v_{2k+1}$ depends only on in which of these paths that $v_{2k}$ resides and whether $v_{2k+1}$ is before or after $v_{2k}$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/lin-kernighan-heuristic] Hence it would be sufficient to examine $2k$ different cases as part of performing step 2.3.2 for $v_{2k-1}$ ; as far as $v_{2k+1}$ is concerned, the outcome of this test can be inherited information rather than something that has to be computed fresh.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] In computer science, **local search** is a heuristic method for solving computationally hard optimization problems.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Local search can be used on problems that can be formulated as finding a solution that maximizes a criterion among a number of candidate solutions.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Local search algorithms move from solution to solution in the space of candidate solutions (the *search space*) by applying local changes, until a solution deemed optimal is found or a time bound is elapsed.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Local search algorithms are widely applied to numerous hard computational problems, including problems from computer science (particularly artificial intelligence), mathematics, operations research, engineering, and bioinformatics.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Examples of local search algorithms are WalkSAT, the 2-opt algorithm for the traveling salesman problem and the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] While it is sometimes possible to substitute gradient descent for a local search algorithm, gradient descent is not in the same family: although it is an iterative method for local optimization, it relies on an objective function’s gradient rather than an explicit exploration of the solution space.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] The Hopfield Neural Networks problem involves finding stable configurations in Hopfield network.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Most problems can be formulated in terms of a search space and target in several different ways.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] For example, for the traveling salesman problem a solution can be a route visiting all cities and the goal is to find the shortest route.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] But a solution can also be a path, and being a cycle is part of the target.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] A local search algorithm starts from a candidate solution and then iteratively moves to a neighboring solution; a neighborhood being the set of all potential solutions that differ from the current solution by the minimal possible extent.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] This requires a neighborhood relation to be defined on the search space.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] As an example, the neighborhood of vertex cover is another vertex cover only differing by one node.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] For Boolean satisfiability, the neighbors of a Boolean assignment are those that have a single variable in an opposite state.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] The same problem may have multiple distinct neighborhoods defined on it; local optimization with neighborhoods that involve changing up to *k* components of the solution is often referred to as **k-opt**.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Typically, every candidate solution has more than one neighbor solution; the choice of which one to select is taken using only information about the solutions in the neighborhood of the current assignment, hence the name *local* search.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] When the choice of the neighbor solution is done by taking the one locally maximizing the criterion, i.e.: a greedy search, the metaheuristic takes the name hill climbing.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] When no improving neighbors are present, local search is stuck at a locally optimal point.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Local search does not provide a guarantee that any given solution is optimal.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] The search can terminate after a given time bound or when the best solution found thus far has not improved in a given number of steps.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Local search is an anytime algorithm; it can return a valid solution even if it's interrupted at any time after finding the first valid solution.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] Local search is typically an approximation or incomplete algorithm because the search may stop even if the current best solution found is not optimal.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] This can happen even if termination happens because the current best solution could not be improved, as the optimal solution can lie far from the neighborhood of the solutions crossed by the algorithm.
[src:lin-kernighan/local-search-optimization] They hypothesize that local search algorithms work well, not because they have some understanding of the search space but because they quickly move to promising regions, and explore the search space at low depths as quickly, broadly, and systematically as possible.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The travelling purchaser problem, the vehicle routing problem and the ring star problem are three generalizations of TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The decision version of the TSP (where given a length *L*, the task is to decide whether the graph has a tour whose length is at most *L*) belongs to the class of NP-complete problems.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Thus, it is possible that the worst-case running time for any algorithm for the TSP increases superpolynomially (but no more than exponentially) with the number of cities.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem was first formulated in 1930 and is one of the most intensively studied problems in optimization.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] It is used as a benchmark for many optimization methods.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Even though the problem is computationally difficult, many heuristics and exact algorithms are known, so that some instances with tens of thousands of cities can be solved completely, and even problems with millions of cities can be approximated within a small fraction of 1%.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP has several applications even in its purest formulation, such as planning, logistics, and the manufacture of microchips.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In warehouse operations, order picking routes are often modelled as variants of the travelling salesman problem, where a picker must visit multiple storage locations and return to a start or drop-off point while minimizing travel distance or time.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Slightly modified, it appears as a sub-problem in many areas, such as DNA sequencing.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In these applications, the concept *city* represents, for example, customers, soldering points, or DNA fragments, and the concept *distance* represents travelling times or cost, or a similarity measure between DNA fragments.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP also appears in astronomy, as astronomers observing many sources want to minimize the time spent moving the telescope between the sources; in such problems, the TSP can be embedded inside an optimal control problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In many applications, additional constraints such as limited resources or time windows may be imposed.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The origins of the travelling salesman problem are unclear.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] A handbook for travelling salesmen from 1832 mentions the problem and includes example tours through Germany and Switzerland, but contains no mathematical treatment.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP was mathematically formulated in the 19th century by the Irish mathematician William Rowan Hamilton and by the British mathematician Thomas Kirkman.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Hamilton's icosian game was a recreational puzzle based on finding a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] It was first considered mathematically in the 1930s by Merrill M.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Flood, who was looking to solve a school bus routing problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Hassler Whitney at Princeton University generated interest in the problem, which he called the "48 states problem".
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the 1950s and 1960s, the problem became increasingly popular in scientific circles in Europe and the United States after the RAND Corporation in Santa Monica offered prizes for steps in solving the problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Notable contributions were made by George Dantzig, Delbert Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Johnson from the RAND Corporation, who expressed the problem as an integer linear program and developed the cutting plane method for its solution.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] They wrote what is considered the seminal paper on the subject in which, with these new methods, they solved an instance with 49 cities to optimality by constructing a tour and proving that no other tour could be shorter.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson, however, speculated that, given a near-optimal solution, one may be able to find optimality or prove optimality by adding a small number of extra inequalities (cuts).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] They used this idea to solve their initial 49-city problem using a string model.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] They found they only needed 26 cuts to come to a solution for their 49 city problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] While this paper did not give an algorithmic approach to TSP problems, the ideas that lay within it were indispensable to later creating exact solution methods for the TSP, though it would take 15 years to find an algorithmic approach in creating these cuts.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] As well as cutting plane methods, Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson used branch-and-bound algorithms perhaps for the first time.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Halton, and John Hammersley published an article entitled "The Shortest Path Through Many Points" in the journal of the Cambridge Philosophical Society.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The Beardwood–Halton–Hammersley theorem provides a practical solution to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The authors derived an asymptotic formula to determine the length of the shortest route for a salesman who starts at a home or office and visits a fixed number of locations before returning to the start.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the following decades, the problem was studied by many researchers from mathematics, computer science, chemistry, physics, and other sciences.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] One method of doing this was to create a minimum spanning tree of the graph and then double all its edges, which produces the bound that the length of an optimal tour is at most twice the weight of a minimum spanning tree.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In 1976, Christofides and Serdyukov (independently of each other) made a big advance in this direction: the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm yields a solution that, in the worst case, is at most 1.5 times longer than the optimal solution.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] As the algorithm was simple and quick, many hoped it would give way to a near-optimal solution method.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] However, this hope for improvement did not immediately materialize, and the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm remained the method with the best worst-case scenario until 2011, when a (very) slightly improved approximation algorithm was developed for the subset of "graphical" TSPs.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In 2020, this tiny improvement was extended to the full (metric) TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Karp showed in 1972 that the Hamiltonian cycle problem was NP-complete, which implies the NP-hardness of TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This supplied a mathematical explanation for the apparent computational difficulty of finding optimal tours.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Great progress was made in the late 1970s and 1980, when Grötschel, Padberg, Rinaldi and others managed to exactly solve instances with up to 2,392 cities, using cutting planes and branch-and-bound.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the 1990s, Applegate, Bixby, Chvátal, and Cook developed the program *Concorde* that has been used in many recent record solutions.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Gerhard Reinelt published the TSPLIB in 1991, a collection of benchmark instances of varying difficulty, which has been used by many research groups for comparing results.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In 2006, Cook and others computed an optimal tour through an 85,900-city instance given by a microchip layout problem, currently the largest solved TSPLIB instance.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For many other instances with millions of cities, solutions can be found that are guaranteed to be within 2–3% of an optimal tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP can be modeled as an undirected weighted graph, such that cities are the graph's vertices, paths are the graph's edges, and a path's distance is the edge's weight.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] It is a minimization problem starting and finishing at a specified vertex after having visited each other vertex exactly once.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Often, the model is a complete graph (i.e., each pair of vertices is connected by an edge).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] If no path exists between two cities, then adding a sufficiently long edge will complete the graph without affecting the optimal tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *symmetric TSP*, the distance between two cities is the same in each opposite direction, forming an undirected graph.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This symmetry halves the number of possible solutions.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *asymmetric TSP*, paths may not exist in both directions or the distances might be different, forming a directed graph.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Traffic congestion, one-way streets, and airfares for cities with different departure and arrival fees are real-world considerations that could yield a TSP problem in asymmetric form.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP can be formulated as an integer linear program.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Two notable formulations are the Miller–Tucker–Zemlin (MTZ) formulation and the Dantzig–Fulkerson–Johnson (DFJ) formulation.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The DFJ formulation is stronger, though the MTZ formulation is still useful in certain settings.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Common to both these formulations is that one labels the cities with the numbers $1,\ldots ,n$ and takes $c_{ij}>0$ to be the cost (distance) from city i to city j .
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] It is because these are 0/1 variables that the formulations become integer programs; all other constraints are purely linear.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Without further constraints, the $\{x_{ij}\}_{i,j}$ will effectively range over all subsets of the set of edges, which is very far from the sets of edges in a tour, and allows for a trivial minimum where all $x_{ij}=0$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The MTZ and DFJ formulations differ in how they express this final requirement as linear constraints.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Merely requiring $u_{j}\geq u_{i}+x_{ij}$ would *not* achieve that, because this also requires $u_{j}\geq u_{i}$ when $x_{ij}=0,$ which is not correct.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The first set of equalities requires that each city is arrived at from exactly one other city, and the second set of equalities requires that from each city there is a departure to exactly one other city.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The last constraint enforces that there is only a single tour covering all cities, and not two or more disjointed tours that only collectively cover all cities.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Take $c_{ij}>0$ to be the distance from city *i* to city *j*.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The last constraint of the DFJ formulation—called a *subtour elimination* constraint—ensures that no proper subset Q can form a sub-tour, so the solution returned is a single tour and not the union of smaller tours.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Intuitively, for each proper subset Q of the cities, the constraint requires that there be fewer edges than cities in Q: if there were to be as many edges in Q as cities in Q, that would represent a subtour of the cities of Q.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Because this leads to an exponential number of possible constraints, in practice it is solved with row generation.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The most direct solution would be to try all permutations (ordered combinations) and see which one is cheapest (using brute-force search).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The running time for this approach lies within a polynomial factor of $O(n!)$ , the factorial of the number of cities, so this solution becomes impractical even for only 20 cities.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] One of the earliest applications of dynamic programming is the Held–Karp algorithm, which solves the problem in time $O(n^{2}2^{n})$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Improving these time bounds seems to be difficult.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, it has not been determined whether a classical exact algorithm for TSP that runs in time $O(1.9999^{n})$ exists.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The currently best quantum exact algorithm for TSP due to Ambainis et al. runs in time $O(1.728^{n})$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] An exact solution for 15,112 German towns from TSPLIB was found in 2001 using the cutting-plane method proposed by George Dantzig, Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Johnson in 1954, based on linear programming.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The computations were performed on a network of 110 processors located at Rice University and Princeton University.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The total computation time was equivalent to 22.6 years on a single 500 MHz Alpha processor.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In May 2004, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 24,978 towns in Sweden was solved: a tour of length approximately 72,500 kilometres was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In March 2005, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 33,810 points in a circuit board was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*: a tour of length 66,048,945 units was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The computation took approximately 15.7 CPU-years (Cook et al.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In April 2006 an instance with 85,900 points was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*, taking over 136 CPU-years; see Applegate et al.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Various heuristics and approximation algorithms, which quickly yield good solutions, have been devised.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] These include the multi-fragment algorithm.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Modern methods can find solutions for extremely large problems (millions of cities) within a reasonable time which are, with a high probability, just 2–3% away from the optimal solution.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Several categories of heuristics are recognized.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The nearest neighbour (NN) algorithm (a greedy algorithm) lets the salesman choose the nearest unvisited city as his next move.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This algorithm quickly yields an effectively short route.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For *N* cities randomly distributed on a plane, the algorithm on average yields a path 25% longer than the shortest possible path; however, there exist many specially-arranged city distributions which make the NN algorithm give the worst route.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This is true for both asymmetric and symmetric TSPs.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Rosenkrantz et al. showed that the NN algorithm has the approximation factor $\Theta (\log |V|)$ for instances satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] A variation of the NN algorithm, called nearest fragment (NF) operator, which connects a group (fragment) of nearest unvisited cities, can find shorter routes with successive iterations.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The NF operator can also be applied on an initial solution obtained by the NN algorithm for further improvement in an elitist model, where only better solutions are accepted.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The bitonic tour of a set of points is the minimum-perimeter monotone polygon that has the points as its vertices; it can be computed efficiently with dynamic programming.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Another constructive heuristic, Match Twice and Stitch (MTS), performs two sequential matchings, where the second matching is executed after deleting all the edges of the first matching, to yield a set of cycles.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The cycles are then stitched to produce the final tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov follows a similar outline but combines the minimum spanning tree with a solution of another problem, minimum-weight perfect matching.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This gives a TSP tour which is at most 1.5 times the optimal.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] It was one of the first approximation algorithms, and was in part responsible for drawing attention to approximation algorithms as a practical approach to intractable problems.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] As a matter of fact, the term "algorithm" was not commonly extended to approximation algorithms until later; the Christofides algorithm was initially referred to as the Christofides heuristic.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This algorithm looks at things differently by using a result from graph theory which helps improve on the lower bound of the TSP which originated from doubling the cost of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Given an Eulerian graph, we can find an Eulerian tour in ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, so if we had an Eulerian graph with cities from a TSP as vertices, then we can easily see that we could use such a method for finding an Eulerian tour to find a TSP solution.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] By the triangle inequality, we know that the TSP tour can be no longer than the Eulerian tour, and we therefore have a lower bound for the TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Create duplicates for every edge to create an Eulerian graph.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Convert to TSP: if a city is visited twice, then create a shortcut from the city before this in the tour to the one after this.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] To improve the lower bound, a better way of creating an Eulerian graph is needed.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] By the triangle inequality, the best Eulerian graph must have the same cost as the best travelling salesman tour; hence, finding optimal Eulerian graphs is at least as hard as TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] One way of doing this is by minimum weight matching using algorithms with a complexity of $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Making a graph into an Eulerian graph starts with the minimum spanning tree; all the vertices of odd order must then be made even, so a matching for the odd-degree vertices must be added, which increases the order of every odd-degree vertex by 1.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This leaves us with a graph where every vertex is of even order, which is thus Eulerian.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Create a matching for the problem with the set of cities of odd order.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The pairwise exchange or 2-opt technique involves iteratively removing two edges and replacing them with two different edges that reconnect the fragments created by edge removal into a new and shorter tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Similarly, the 3-opt technique removes 3 edges and reconnects them to form a shorter tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] These are special cases of the *k*-opt method.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The label *Lin–Kernighan* is an often heard misnomer for 2-opt; Lin–Kernighan is actually the more general *k*-opt method.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For Euclidean instances, 2-opt heuristics give on average solutions that are about 5% better than those yielded by Christofides' algorithm.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] If we start with an initial solution made with a greedy algorithm, then the average number of moves greatly decreases again and is ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠; however, for random starts, the average number of moves is ⁠ $O(n\log(n))$ ⁠.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] While this is a small increase in size, the initial number of moves for small problems is 10 times as big for a random start compared to one made from a greedy heuristic.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This is because such 2-opt heuristics exploit 'bad' parts of a solution such as crossings.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] These types of heuristics are often used within vehicle routing problem heuristics to re-optimize route solutions.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The Lin–Kernighan heuristic is a special case of the *V*-opt or variable-opt technique.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Reassemble the remaining fragments into a tour, leaving no disjoint subtours (that is, do not connect a fragment's endpoints together).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This in effect simplifies the TSP under consideration into a much simpler problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Each fragment endpoint can be connected to 2*k* − 2 other possibilities: of 2*k* total fragment endpoints available, the two endpoints of the fragment under consideration are disallowed.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Such a constrained 2*k*-city TSP can then be solved with brute-force methods to find the least-cost recombination of the original fragments.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The most popular of the *k*-opt methods are 3-opt, as introduced by Shen Lin of Bell Labs in 1965.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] A special case of 3-opt is where the edges are not disjoint (two of the edges are adjacent to one another).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In practice, it is often possible to achieve substantial improvement over 2-opt without the combinatorial cost of the general 3-opt by restricting the 3-changes to this special subset where two of the removed edges are adjacent.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This so-called two-and-a-half-opt typically falls roughly midway between 2-opt and 3-opt, both in terms of the quality of tours achieved and the time required to achieve those tours.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The variable-opt method is related to, and a generalization of, the *k*-opt method.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Whereas the *k*-opt methods remove a fixed number (*k*) of edges from the original tour, the variable-opt methods do not fix the size of the edge set to remove.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Instead, they grow the set as the search process continues.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The best-known method in this family is the Lin–Kernighan method (mentioned above as a misnomer for 2-opt).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Shen Lin and Brian Kernighan first published their method in 1972, and it was the most reliable heuristic for solving travelling salesman problems for nearly two decades.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] More advanced variable-opt methods were developed at Bell Labs in the late 1980s by David Johnson and his research team.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] These methods (sometimes called Lin–Kernighan–Johnson) build on the Lin–Kernighan method, adding ideas from tabu search and evolutionary computing.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The basic Lin–Kernighan technique gives results that are guaranteed to be at least 3-opt.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The Lin–Kernighan–Johnson methods compute a Lin–Kernighan tour, and then perturb the tour by what has been described as a mutation that removes at least four edges and reconnects the tour in a different way, then *V*-opting the new tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The mutation is often enough to move the tour from the local minimum identified by Lin–Kernighan.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] *V*-opt methods are widely considered the most powerful heuristics for the problem, and are able to address special cases, such as the Hamilton Cycle Problem and other non-metric TSPs that other heuristics fail on.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For many years, Lin–Kernighan–Johnson had identified optimal solutions for all TSPs where an optimal solution was known and had identified the best-known solutions for all other TSPs on which the method had been tried.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Optimized Markov chain algorithms which use local searching heuristic sub-algorithms can find a route extremely close to the optimal route for 700 to 800 cities.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP is a touchstone for many general heuristics devised for combinatorial optimization such as genetic algorithms, simulated annealing, tabu search, ant colony optimization, river formation dynamics (see swarm intelligence), and the cross entropy method.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This starts with a sub-tour such as the convex hull and then inserts other vertices.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Artificial intelligence researcher Marco Dorigo described in 1993 a method of heuristically generating "good solutions" to the TSP using a simulation of an ant colony called *ACS* (*ant colony system*).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] It models behavior observed in real ants to find short paths between food sources and their nest, an emergent behavior resulting from each ant's preference to follow trail pheromones deposited by other ants.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] ACS sends out a large number of virtual ant agents to explore many possible routes on the map.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Each ant probabilistically chooses the next city to visit based on a heuristic combining the distance to the city and the amount of virtual pheromone deposited on the edge to the city.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The ants explore, depositing pheromone on each edge that they cross, until they have all completed a tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] At this point the ant which completed the shortest tour deposits virtual pheromone along its complete tour route (*global trail updating*).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The amount of pheromone deposited is inversely proportional to the tour length: the shorter the tour, the more it deposits.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the *metric TSP*, also known as *delta-TSP* or Δ-TSP, the intercity distances satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The edges then build a metric on the set of vertices.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] When the cities are viewed as points in the plane, many natural distance functions are metrics, and so many natural instances of TSP satisfy this constraint.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The following are some examples of metric TSPs for various metrics.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The last two metrics appear, for example, in routing a machine that drills a given set of holes in a printed circuit board.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The Manhattan metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts first one coordinate, and then the other, so the time to move to a new point is the sum of both movements.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The maximum metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts both coordinates simultaneously, so the time to move to a new point is the slower of the two movements.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In its definition, the TSP does not allow cities to be visited twice, but many applications do not need this constraint.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In such cases, a symmetric, non-metric instance can be reduced to a metric one.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This replaces the original graph with a complete graph in which the inter-city distance $d_{AB}$ is replaced by the shortest path length between *A* and *B* in the original graph.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For points in the Euclidean plane, the optimal solution to the travelling salesman problem forms a simple polygon through all of the points, a polygonalization of the points.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Any non-optimal solution with crossings can be made into a shorter solution without crossings by local optimizations.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The Euclidean distance obeys the triangle inequality, so the Euclidean TSP forms a special case of metric TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] However, even when the input points have integer coordinates, their distances generally take the form of square roots, and the length of a tour is a sum of radicals, making it difficult to perform the symbolic computation needed to perform exact comparisons of the lengths of different tours.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Like the general TSP, the exact Euclidean TSP is NP-hard, but the issue with sums of radicals is an obstacle to proving that its decision version is in NP, and therefore NP-complete.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] A discretized version of the problem with distances rounded to integers is NP-complete.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] With rational coordinates and the actual Euclidean metric, Euclidean TSP is known to be in the Counting Hierarchy, a subclass of PSPACE.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] With arbitrary real coordinates, Euclidean TSP cannot be in such classes, since there are uncountably many possible inputs.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Despite these complications, Euclidean TSP is much easier than the general metric case for approximation.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, the minimum spanning tree of the graph associated with an instance of the Euclidean TSP is a Euclidean minimum spanning tree, and so can be computed in expected *O*(*n* log *n*) time for *n* points (considerably less than the number of edges).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This enables the simple 2-approximation algorithm for TSP with triangle inequality above to operate more quickly.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] time; this is called a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Mitchell were awarded the Gödel Prize in 2010 for their concurrent discovery of a PTAS for the Euclidean TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In practice, simpler heuristics with weaker guarantees continue to be used.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In most cases, the distance between two nodes in the TSP network is the same in both directions.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The case where the distance from *A* to *B* is not equal to the distance from *B* to *A* is called asymmetric TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] A practical application of an asymmetric TSP is route optimization using street-level routing (which is made asymmetric by one-way streets, slip-roads, motorways, etc.).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The stacker crane problem can be viewed as a special case of the asymmetric TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In this problem, the input consists of ordered pairs of points in a metric space, which must be visited consecutively in order by the tour.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] These pairs of points can be viewed as the nodes of an asymmetric TSP, with asymmetric distances reflecting the combined cost of traveling from the first point of a pair to its second and then from the second point of a pair to the first point of the next pair.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Solving an asymmetric TSP graph can be somewhat complex.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The following is a 3×3 matrix containing all possible path weights between the nodes *A*, *B* and *C*.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] One option is to turn an asymmetric matrix of size *N* into a symmetric matrix of size 2*N*.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] To double the size, each of the nodes in the graph is duplicated, creating a second *ghost node*, linked to the original node with a "ghost" edge of very low (possibly negative) weight, here denoted −*w*.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] (Alternatively, the ghost edges have weight 0, and weight w is added to all other edges.) The original 3×3 matrix shown above is visible in the bottom left and the transpose of the original in the top-right.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Both copies of the matrix have had their diagonals replaced by the low-cost hop paths, represented by −*w*.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the new graph, no edge directly links original nodes and no edge directly links ghost nodes.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The weight −*w* of the "ghost" edges linking the ghost nodes to the corresponding original nodes must be low enough to ensure that all ghost edges must belong to any optimal symmetric TSP solution on the new graph (*w* = 0 is not always low enough).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] There is an analogous problem in geometric measure theory which asks the following: under what conditions may a subset *E* of Euclidean space be contained in a rectifiable curve (that is, when is there a curve with finite length that visits every point in *E*)?
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This problem is known as the analyst's travelling salesman problem.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Suppose $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are n independent random variables with uniform distribution in the square $[0,1]^{2}$ , and let $L_{n}^{\ast }$ be the shortest path length (i.e.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] TSP solution) for this set of points, according to the usual Euclidean distance.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] where $\beta$ is a positive constant that is not known explicitly.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Since $L_{n}^{*}\leq 2{\sqrt {n}}+2$ (see below), it follows from bounded convergence theorem that $\beta =\lim _{n\to \infty }\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]/{\sqrt {n}}$ , hence lower and upper bounds on $\beta$ follow from bounds on $\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The almost-sure limit ${\frac {L_{n}^{*}}{\sqrt {n}}}\rightarrow \beta$ as $n\to \infty$ may not exist if the independent locations $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are replaced with observations from a stationary ergodic process with uniform marginals.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Held and Karp gave a polynomial-time algorithm that provides numerical lower bounds for $L_{n}^{*}$ , and thus for $\beta (\simeq L_{n}^{*}/{\sqrt {n}})$ , which seem to be good up to more or less 1%.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] where 0.522 comes from the points near the square boundary which have fewer neighbours, and Christine L.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem has been shown to be NP-hard (more precisely, it is complete for the complexity class FPNP; see function problem), and the decision problem version ("given the costs and a number *x*, decide whether there is a round-trip route cheaper than *x*") is NP-complete.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The bottleneck travelling salesman problem is also NP-hard.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The problem remains NP-hard even for the case when the cities are in the plane with Euclidean distances, as well as in a number of other restrictive cases.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Removing the condition of visiting each city "only once" does not remove the NP-hardness, since in the planar case there is an optimal tour that visits each city only once (otherwise, by the triangle inequality, a shortcut that skips a repeated visit would not increase the tour length).
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the general case, finding a shortest travelling salesman tour is NPO-complete.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance measure is a metric (and thus symmetric), the problem becomes APX-complete, and the algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov approximates it within 1.5.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distances are restricted to 1 and 2 (but still are a metric), then the approximation ratio becomes 8/7.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the asymmetric case with triangle inequality, in 2018, a constant factor approximation was developed by Svensson, Tarnawski, and Végh.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] An algorithm by Vera Traub and Jens Vygen achieves a performance ratio of $22+\varepsilon$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This factor was further improved to $17+\varepsilon$ .
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The best known inapproximability bound is 75/74.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The corresponding maximization problem of finding the *longest* travelling salesman tour is approximable within 63/38.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance function is symmetric, then the longest tour can be approximated within 4/3 by a deterministic algorithm and within $(33+\varepsilon )/25$ by a randomized algorithm.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The TSP, in particular the Euclidean variant of the problem, has attracted the attention of researchers in cognitive psychology.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] It has been observed that humans are able to produce near-optimal solutions quickly, in a close-to-linear fashion, with performance that ranges from 1% less efficient, for graphs with 10–20 nodes, to 11% less efficient for graphs with 120 nodes.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The apparent ease with which humans accurately generate near-optimal solutions to the problem has led researchers to hypothesize that humans use one or more heuristics, with the two most popular theories arguably being the convex-hull hypothesis and the crossing-avoidance heuristic.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] However, additional evidence suggests that human performance is quite varied, and individual differences as well as graph geometry appear to affect performance in the task.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Nevertheless, results suggest that computer performance on the TSP may be improved by understanding and emulating the methods used by humans for these problems, and have also led to new insights into the mechanisms of human thought.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The first issue of the *Journal of Problem Solving* was devoted to the topic of human performance on TSP, and a 2011 review listed dozens of papers on the subject.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the first experiment, pigeons were placed in the corner of a lab room and allowed to fly to nearby feeders containing peas.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] The researchers found that pigeons largely used proximity to determine which feeder they would select next.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] In the second experiment, the feeders were arranged in such a way that flying to the nearest feeder at every opportunity would be largely inefficient if the pigeons needed to visit every feeder.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] This suggests non-primates may possess a relatively sophisticated spatial cognitive ability.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Humans are not the only species to show excellent efficiency.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, when presented with a spatial configuration of food sources, the amoeboid *Physarum polycephalum* adapts its morphology to create an efficient path between the food sources, which can also be viewed as an approximate solution to TSP.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Similarly, honey bees and bumblebees have been shown to be very adept at maximising efficiency to a very high degree of accuracy when collecting nectar and pollen by using collective intelligence.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] For benchmarking of TSP algorithms, TSPLIB is a library of sample instances of the TSP and related problems.
[src:lin-kernighan/travelling-salesman-problem] Many of them are lists of actual cities and layouts of actual printed circuits.
